<subSubSection id="60A26544FFC5FFE8FF14F818FD88FA49" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="65" pageId="21" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="280736CFFFC5FFEBFF14F818FA79FFAB" blockId="21.[151,1436,1955,2016]" box="[199,1436,1991,2016]" pageId="21" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="1ACCEADDFFC5FFEBFF14F818FED8FF94" bold="true" box="[199,317,1991,2016]" pageId="21" pageNumber="64">Remarks:</emphasis>
This single specimen is poorly preserved and oriented so that an adequate description is not
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="280736CFFFC6FFE8FF44FF48FD88FA49" blockId="22.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="22" pageNumber="65">
possible. But it is remarkable in that only a very small number of marine eutardigrades are known. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="EFB84D4CFFC6FFE8FF44FF63FE0CF8A0" authority="Kristensen, 1982" authorityName="Kristensen" authorityYear="1982" box="[151,489,188,213]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Hypsibiidae" genus="Halobiotus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1ACCEADDFFC6FFE8FF44FF63FEF1F8A1" box="[151,276,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="65">Halobiotus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4C294B3EFFC6FFE8FEF0FF63FE0CF8A0" box="[291,489,188,213]" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" refId="ref15779" refString="Kristensen, R. M. (1982) The first record of cyclomorphosis in Tardigrada based on a new genus and species from Arctic meiobenthos. Zeitschrift fur Zoologische systematic and Evolution Forschung, 20, 249 - 270. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1439 - 0469.1983. tb 00552. x" type="journal article">Kristensen, 1982</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is secondarily adapted to saltwater environments in northern latitudes, as is, apparently, 
<taxonomicName id="EFB84D4CFFC6FFE8FEC8FF00FD96F88C" authority="Tsurusaki, 1980" authorityName="Tsurusaki" authorityYear="1980" box="[283,627,223,248]" class="Heterotardigrada" family="Hypsibiidae" genus="Thulinius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="itoi">
<emphasis id="1ACCEADDFFC6FFE8FEC8FF00FE56F88C" box="[283,435,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="65">Thulinius itoi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4C294B3EFFC6FFE8FE68FF00FD96F88C" box="[443,627,223,248]" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" refId="ref17704" refString="Tsurusaki, N. (1980) A new species of marine Tardigrada of the genus Hypsibius from Hokkaido, Northern Japan. Annotations Zoologicae Japonense, 53, 280 - 284." type="journal article">Tsurusaki, 1980</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. All were described from intertidal or supralittoral sand. Our specimen was found in sand at 
<quantity id="EF409B2AFFC6FFE8FE5CFEDBFE59F968" box="[399,444,260,284]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" unit="m" value="3.0">3 m</quantity>
depth, over 
<quantity id="EF409B2AFFC6FFE8FD9CFEDBFD43F968" box="[591,678,260,284]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</quantity>
from the nearest shore. Is it a truly marine species or a terrestrial species that was an “accidental” in these samples? The distance from shore might suggest the former hypothesis, while the lone occurrence supports the latter. The specimen has a granulated cuticle without gibbosities, no visible eyes, 
<taxonomicName id="EFB84D4CFFC6FFE8FF05FEB0FEA3F9FC" authorityName="Ehrenberg" authorityYear="1848" box="[214,326,367,392]" class="Heterotardigrada" family="Hypsibiidae" genus="Hypsibius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1ACCEADDFFC6FFE8FF05FEB0FEA3F9FC" box="[214,326,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="65">Hypsibius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- 
<typeStatus id="F703886DFFC6FFE8FE9EFEAFFE9AF9FC" box="[333,383,368,392]" pageId="22" pageNumber="65">type</typeStatus>
claws with thick primary branches and well-developed accessory points, light refracting areas at the base of primary branches of all claws, lack of claw lunules, and a pharynx with two small macroplacoids (the first pear-shaped and larger than the second) and a minute roundish microplacoid/septula. Together with some morphometric characters, this does not match any currently known 
<taxonomicName id="EFB84D4CFFC6FFE8FC48FE03FBEEF981" authorityName="Ehrenberg" authorityYear="1848" box="[923,1035,476,501]" class="Heterotardigrada" family="Hypsibiidae" genus="Hypsibius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="22" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1ACCEADDFFC6FFE8FC48FE03FBEEF981" box="[923,1035,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="65">Hypsibius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. It seems to us improbable that an accidental terrestrial specimen would also be a species never before encountered. Further sampling is needed to resolve this intriguing question.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
